A vintage 1970s computer terminal in warm sepia and amber tones, displaying streams of flowing data cascading down the screen like a waterfall. In the foreground, a mechanical mail sorting machine with brass gears and copper tubes automatically processes dozens of cream-colored envelopes, each envelope splitting into multiple copies as they travel along conveyor belts. The envelopes fan out in a mesmerizing spiral pattern, suggesting multiplication and automation. Dust motes float in dramatic shaft lighting from a nearby window. The scene has the aesthetic of an old post office merged with early computing machinery, with analog dials, punch cards scattered on a wooden desk, and a steaming coffee cup nearby. Rich browns, golds, and deep burgundy dominate the color palette.
